{"solution":"**Understanding**

Your spread created the `identity` member on the resource type itself, so without versioning it appears in **all** API versions. The right fix is to keep the spread, then version the **resulting spread property** with the augment form of `@added` from the TypeSpec versioning library.

**Key guidance to follow**

- Use `@@added` on the generated property, not on `Azure.ResourceManager.ManagedServiceIdentityProperty` itself. See [TypeSpec ARM versioning](https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/howtos/arm/versioning).
- `ManagedServiceIdentityProperty` comes from the ARM library and expands to `identity?`; version that concrete member on your resource model. See [ManagedServiceIdentityProperty](https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/libraries/azure-resource-manager/reference/data-types).
- If you also introduced identity into a PATCH/update model, version that model’s `identity` member separately too.

**Step-by-step plan**

1. Keep your existing spread on the resource model.
2. Ensure you import/use the versioning library from [TypeSpec versioning guidance](https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/howtos/versioning/06-evolving-apis).
3. Add an augment decorator after the model:
   ```typespec
   @@added(YourResource.identity, Versions.`2025-05-04-preview`);
   ```
4. Repeat for any other model that gained `identity` only in that version.

**Diff outline**

```typespec
// Before
model MyResource is TrackedResource<MyResourceProperties> {
  ...ResourceNameParameter<MyResource>;
  ...Azure.ResourceManager.ManagedServiceIdentityProperty;
}

// After
model MyResource is TrackedResource<MyResourceProperties> {
  ...ResourceNameParameter<MyResource>;
  ...Azure.ResourceManager.ManagedServiceIdentityProperty;
}

@@added(MyResource.identity, Versions.`2025-05-04-preview`);
```

**Complete example**

```typespec
import "@typespec/versioning";
import "@azure-tools/typespec-azure-resource-manager";

using TypeSpec.Versioning;
using Azure.ResourceManager;

@versioned(Versions)
namespace Microsoft.Contoso;

enum Versions {
  @useDependency(Azure.ResourceManager.Versions.v1_0_Preview_1)
  @armCommonTypesVersion(Azure.ResourceManager.CommonTypes.Versions.v5)
  `2024-10-01`,

  @useDependency(Azure.ResourceManager.Versions.v1_0_Preview_1)
  @armCommonTypesVersion(Azure.ResourceManager.CommonTypes.Versions.v5)
  `2025-05-04-preview`,
}

model MyResourceProperties {}

model MyResource is TrackedResource<MyResourceProperties> {
  ...ResourceNameParameter<MyResource>;
  ...ManagedServiceIdentityProperty;
}

@@added(MyResource.identity, Versions.`2025-05-04-preview`);
```

**Validation plan**

- Run `tsp compile .`
- Check emitted `2024-10-01` output: `identity` should be absent.
- Check emitted `2025-05-04-preview` output: `identity` should be present.

**Risks & mitigations**

- **Wrong target symbol**: if the spread is on the resource, target `MyResource.identity`, not `MyResourceProperties.identity`.
- **PATCH still breaks older versions**: also version `UpdateModel.identity` if applicable.
- **Version typo**: use the exact enum member name, including backticks for `2025-05-04-preview`.","references":[{"title":"Versioning | Simple Scenarios","source":"","link":"https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/howtos/arm/versioning","snippet":""},{"title":"Evolving APIs using the Versioning Library","source":"","link":"https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/howtos/versioning/06-evolving-apis","snippet":""},{"title":"ManagedServiceIdentityProperty reference","source":"","link":"https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/libraries/azure-resource-manager/reference/data-types","snippet":""}],"typespec_project":"","package_type":"Unknown","language":"TypeSpec","operation_status":"Succeeded"}

